TE) provide the synchronization mechanism. Integration-level testing with concurrent async tasks against a real database is sufficient to trigger and catch race conditions. Mock-hide: mocking cannot model true concurrent access or database locking behavior.","test_description":"Create a test PostgreSQL database with _migrations table and two migration files. Use Promise.all() or similar to spawn two concurrent async tasks, each running the migration runner against the same database. Verify: both tasks complete successfully, each migration is recorded in _migrations exactly once (not twice), and both tasks see consistent results. Verify the runner uses SELECT FOR UPDATE or similar locking on the metadata table to serialize migration application.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.83,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On the very first run against a fresh database, the _migrations table is created before any migration file is applied.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The failure mode (table created after migrations, or not created at all, or errors on second run) is a local control-flow issue in the runner. Mock the database, verify that the CREATE TABLE statement is called before any migration execute() calls, and verify the create is idempotent.","test_description":"Mock the PostgreSQL connection. Run the migration runner for the first time against a fresh database (no _migrations table exists in the mock). Verify that a CREATE TABLE _migrations statement is issued before any migration SQL is executed. Verify the runner does not error if the table already exists on a second run (idempotency). Check call order: createTable() before execute().","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.78,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":nul